From  (G5228) huper and the base of  (G939) basis; to transcend, i.e. (figuratively) to overreach -- go beyond. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G939) basis
Adverb from present participle active of  (G5235) huperballo; excessively -- beyond measure. see GREEK  (G5235) huperballo

column7: to throw over or beyond, to run beyond
column9: From  (G5228) huper and  (G906) ballo; to throw beyod the usual mark, i.e. (figuratively) to surpass (only active participle supereminent) -- exceeding, excel, pass. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G906) ballo

From  (G5235) huperballo; a throwing beyond others, i.e. (figuratively) supereminence; adverbially (with  (G1519) eis or  (G2596) kata) pre- eminently -- abundance, (far more) exceeding, excellency, more excellent, beyond (out of) measure. see GREEK  (G5235) huperballo see GREEK  (G1519) eis see GREEK  (G2596) kata
From  (G5228) huper and  (G1492) eido; to overlook, i.e. Not punish -- wink at. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G1492) eido
From  (G5228) huper and the neuter plural of  (G1565) ekeinos; above those parts, i.e. Still farther -- beyond. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G1565) ekeinos
From  (G5228) huper and  (G1614) ekteino; to extend inordinately -- stretch beyond. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G1614) ekteino

column7: to pour out over, to overflow
column9: From  (G5228) huper and the alternate form of  (G1632) ekcheo; to pour out over, i.e. (passively) to overflow -- run over. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G1632) ekcheo

column7: to intercede, to make petition for
column9: From  (G5228) huper and  (G1793) entugchano; to intercede in behalf of -- make intercession for see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G1793) entugchano

column7: to hold above, to rise above, to be superior
column9: From  (G5228) huper and  (G2192) echo; to hold oneself above, i.e. (figuratively) to excel; participle (as adjective, or neuter as noun) superior, superiority -- better, excellency, higher, pass, supreme. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G2192) echo
From  (G5244) huperephanos; haughtiness -- pride. see GREEK  (G5244) huperephanos
From  (G5228) huper and  (G5316) phaino; appearing above others (conspicuous), i.e. (figuratively) haughty -- proud. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G5316) phaino
From  (G5228) huper and  (G3528) nikao; to vanquish beyond, i.e. Gain a decisive victory -- more than conquer. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G3528) nikao
From  (G5228) huper and  (G3591) ogkos; bulging over, i.e. (figuratively) insolent -- great swelling. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G3591) ogkos
From  (G5242) huperecho; prominence, i.e. (figuratively) superiority (in rank or character) -- authority, excellency. see GREEK  (G5242) huperecho
From  (G5228) huper and  (G4052) perisseuo; to super-abound -- abound much more, exceeding. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G4052) perisseuo
From  (G5228) huper and  (G4057) perissos; superabundantly, i.e. Exceedingly -- beyond measure. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G4057) perissos
From  (G5228) huper and  (G4121) pleonazo; to superabound -- be exceeding abundant. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G4121) pleonazo
From  (G5228) huper and  (G5312) hupsoo; to elevate above others, i.e. Raise to the highest position -- highly exalt. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G5312) hupsoo

column7: to be overly proud, to have high thoughts
column9: From  (G5228) huper and  (G5426) phroneo; to esteem oneself overmuch, i.e. Be vain or arrogant -- think more highly. see GREEK  (G5228) huper see GREEK  (G5426) phroneo

column7: the upper story, the upper rooms
column9: Neuter of a derivative of  (G5228) huper; a higher part of the house, i.e. Apartment in the third story -- upper chamber (room). see GREEK  (G5228) huper

column7: to hold or put under, to undergo
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G2192) echo; to hold oneself under, i.e. Endure with patience -- suffer. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G2192) echo
From  (G5219) hupakouo; attentively listening, i.e. (by implication) submissive -- obedient. see GREEK  (G5219) hupakouo

column7: to serve as a rower, to minister to, serve
column9: From  (G5257) huperetes; to be a subordinate, i.e. (by implication) subserve -- minister (unto), serve. see GREEK  (G5257) huperetes
From  (G5259) hupo and a derivative of eresso (to row); an under-oarsman, i.e. (generally) subordinate (assistant, sexton, constable) -- minister, officer, servant. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo
From an obsolete primary (perhaps akin to  (G5259) hupo through the idea of subsilience); sleep, i.e. (figuratively) spiritual torpor -- sleep. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo

column8: by, from, in, of, under, with.
column9: A primary preposition; under, i.e. (with the genitive case) of place (beneath), or with verbs (the agency or means, through); (with the accusative case) of place (whither (underneath) or where (below) or time (when (at)) -- among, by, from, in, of, under, with. In the comparative, it retains the same general applications, especially of inferior position or condition, and specially, covertly or moderately.
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G906) ballo; to throw in stealthily, i.e. Introduce by collusion -- suborn. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G906) ballo

column7: a writing to be copied, an example
column9: From a compound of  (G5259) hupo and  (G1125) grapho; an underwriting, i.e. Copy for imitation (figuratively) -- example. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G1125) grapho
From  (G5263) hupodeiknumi; an exhibit for imitation or warning (figuratively, specimen, adumbration) -- en-(ex-)ample, pattern. see GREEK  (G5263) hupodeiknumi

column7: to show secretly, to show by tracing out, to teach, make known
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G1166) deiknuo; to exhibit under the eyes, i.e. (figuratively) to exemplify (instruct, admonish) -- show, (fore-)warn. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G1166) deiknuo

column7: to receive under one\'s roof, to receive as a guest
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G1209) dechomai; to admit under one's roof, i.e. Entertain hospitably -- receive. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G1209) dechomai
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G1210) deo; to bind under one's feet, i.e. Put on shoes or sandals -- bind on, (be) shod. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G1210) deo

column7: a sole bound under (the foot), a sandal
column9: From  (G5265) hupodeo; something bound under the feet, i.e. A shoe or sandal -- shoe. see GREEK  (G5265) hupodeo
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G1349) dike; under sentence, i.e. (by implication) condemned -- guilty. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G1349) dike

column7: a beast of burden or draught
column9: Neuter of a compound of  (G5259) hupo and  (G2218) zugos; an animal under the yoke (draught-beast), i.e. (specially), a donkey -- ass. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G2218) zugos
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G2224) zonnumi; to gird under, i.e. Frap (a vessel with cables across the keel, sides and deck) -- undergirt. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G2224) zonnumi
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G2736) kato; down under, i.e. Beneath -- under. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G2736) kato

column7: to answer, reply, to answer on a stage, to pretend
column9: Middle voice from  (G5259) hupo and  (G2919) krino; to decide (speak or act) under a false part, i.e. (figuratively) dissemble (pretend) -- feign. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G2919) krino
From  (G5271) hupokrinomai; acting under a feigned part, i.e. (figuratively) deceit ("hypocrisy") -- condemnation, dissimulation, hypocrisy. see GREEK  (G5271) hupokrinomai

column7: one who answers, an actor, a hypocrite
column9: From  (G5271) hupokrinomai; an actor under an assumed character (stage-player), i.e. (figuratively) a dissembler ("hypocrite" -- hypocrite. see GREEK  (G5271) hupokrinomai

column7: to take or bear up, to receive, to assume
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G2983) lambano; to take from below, i.e. Carry upward; figuratively, to take up, i.e. Continue a discourse or topic; mentally, to assume (presume) -- answer, receive, suppose. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G2983) lambano
From  (G5295) hupotrecho and  (G3007) leipo; to leave under (behind), i.e. (passively) to remain (survive) -- be left. see GREEK  (G5295) hupotrecho see GREEK  (G3007) leipo

column7: a vessel or trough beneath a winepress (to receive the juice)
column9: Neuter of a presumed compound of  (G5259) hupo and  (G3025) lenos; vessel or receptacle under the press, i.e. Lower wine-vat -- winefat. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G3025) lenos
A prolonged form for  (G5275) hupoleipo; to leave behind, i.e. Bequeath -- leave. see GREEK  (G5275) hupoleipo

column7: to stay behind, to await, endure
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G3306) meno; to stay under (behind), i.e. Remain; figuratively, to undergo, i.e. Bear (trials), have fortitude, persevere -- abide, endure, (take) patient(-ly), suffer, tarry behind. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G3306) meno

column7: to cause (one) to remember, to remind
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G3403) mimnesko; to remind quietly, i.e. Suggest to the (middle voice, one's own) memory -- put in mind, remember, bring to (put in) remembrance. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G3403) mimnesko
From  (G5279) hupomimnesko; a reminding or (reflexively) recollection -- remembrance. see GREEK  (G5279) hupomimnesko

column7: a remaining behind, a patient enduring
column9: From  (G5278) hupomeno; cheerful (or hopeful) endurance, constancy -- enduring, patience, patient continuance (waiting). see GREEK  (G5278) hupomeno
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G3539) noieo; to think under (privately), i.e. To surmise or conjecture -- think, suppose, deem. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G3539) noieo
From  (G5282) huponoeo; suspicion -- surmising. see GREEK  (G5282) huponoeo

column7: to sail under (i.e. under the lee of)
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G4126) pleo; to sail under the lee of -- sail under. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G4126) pleo
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G4154) pneo; to breathe gently, i.e. Breeze -- blow softly. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G4154) pneo
Neuter of a compound of  (G5259) hupo and  (G4228) pous; something under the feet, i.e. A foot-rest (figuratively) -- footstool. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G4228) pous

From a compound of  (G5259) hupo and  (G2476) histemi; a setting under (support), i.e. (figuratively) concretely, essence, or abstractly, assurance (objectively or subjectively) -- confidence, confident, person, substance. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G2476) histemi

column7: to draw in, let down, draw back
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G4724) stello; to withhold under (out of sight), i.e. (reflexively) to cower or shrink, (figuratively) to conceal (reserve) -- draw (keep) back, shun, withdraw. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G4724) stello

column7: a letting down, a shrinking back
column9: From  (G5288) hupostello; shrinkage (timidity), i.e. (by implication) apostasy -- draw back. see GREEK  (G5288) hupostello

From  (G5259) hupo and  (G4762) strepho; to turn under (behind), i.e. To return (literally or figuratively) -- come again, return (again, back again), turn back (again). see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G4762) strepho
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G4766) stronnumi; to strew underneath (the feet as a carpet) -- spread. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G4766) stronnumi
From  (G5293) hupotasso; subordination -- subjection. see GREEK  (G5293) hupotasso

column7: to place or rank under, to subject, mid. to obey
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G5021) tasso; to subordinate; reflexively, to obey -- be under obedience (obedient), put under, subdue unto, (be, make) subject (to, unto), be (put) in subjection (to, under), submit self unto. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G5021) tasso

column7: to place under, lay down, mid. to suggest
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G5087) tithemi; to place underneath, i.e. (figuratively) to hazard, (reflexively) to suggest -- lay down, put in remembrance. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G5087) tithemi
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G5143) trecho (including its alternate); to run under, i.e. (specially), to sail past -- run under. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G5143) trecho

From a compound of  (G5259) hupo and a derivative of  (G5179) tupos; typification under (after), i.e. (concretely) a sketch (figuratively) for imitation -- form, pattern. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G5179) tupos

column7: to bear by being under, to endure
column9: From  (G5259) hupo and  (G5342) phero; to bear from underneath, i.e. (figuratively) to undergo hardship -- bear, endure. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G5342) phero
From  (G5259) hupo and  (G5562) choreo; to vacate down, i.e. Retire quietly -- go aside, withdraw self. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G5562) choreo

From a compound of  (G5259) hupo and a derivative of  (G3700) optanomai; to hit under the eye (buffet or disable an antagonist as a pugilist), i.e. (figuratively) to tease or annoy (into compliance), subdue (one's passions) -- keep under, weary. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo see GREEK  (G3700) optanomai
Apparently a primary word; a hog ("swine") -- sow.
Of foreign origin ( (H231) 'ezowb); "hyssop" -- hyssop. see HEBREW  (H231) 'ezowb

column7: to come late, be behind, come short
column9: From  (G5306) husteros; to be later, i.e. (by implication) to be inferior; generally, to fall short (be deficient) -- come behind (short), be destitute, fail, lack, suffer need, (be in) want, be the worse. see GREEK  (G5306) husteros
From  (G5302) hustereo; a deficit; specially, poverty -- that which is behind, (that which was) lack(-ing), penury, want. see GREEK  (G5302) hustereo
A falling short, i.e. (specially), penury -- want.
Neuter of  (G5306) husteros as adverb; more lately, i.e. Eventually -- afterward, (at the) last (of all). see GREEK  (G5306) husteros
Comparative from  (G5259) hupo (in the sense of behind); later -- latter. see GREEK  (G5259) hupo
From huphaino to weave; woven, i.e. (perhaps) knitted -- woven.
From  (G5311) hupsos; lofty (in place or character) -- high(-er, -ly) (esteemed). see GREEK  (G5311) hupsos
From a compound of  (G5308) hupselos and  (G5424) phren; to be lofty in mind, i.e. Arrogant -- be highminded. see GREEK  (G5308) hupselos see GREEK  (G5424) phren
Superlative from the base of  (G5311) hupsos; highest, i.e. (masculine singular) the Supreme (God), or (neuter plural) the heavens -- most high, highest. see GREEK  (G5311) hupsos
From a derivative of  (G5228) huper; elevation, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, (specially), the sky, or (figuratively) dignity -- be exalted, height, (on) high. see GREEK  (G5228) huper

column7: to lift or raise up, to exalt, uplift
column9: From  (G5311) hupsos; to elevate (literally or figuratively) -- exalt, lift up. see GREEK  (G5311) hupsos

column7: height, that which is lifted up
column9: From  (G5312) hupsoo; an elevated place or thing, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, or (by implication) a barrier (figuratively) -- height, high thing. see GREEK  (G5312) hupsoo
From  (G5315) phago; a glutton -- gluttonous. see GREEK  (G5315) phago
A primary verb (used as an alternate of  (G2068) esthio in certain tenses); to eat (literally or figuratively) -- eat, meat. see GREEK  (G2068) esthio

column7: to bring to light, to cause to appear
column9: Prolongation for the base of  (G5457) phos; to lighten (shine), i.e. Show (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative) -- appear, seem, be seen, shine, X think. see GREEK  (G5457) phos
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6389) Peleg); Phalek (i.e. Peleg), a patriarch -- Phalec. see HEBREW  (H6389) Peleg

From  (G5316) phaino; shining, i.e. Apparent (literally or figuratively); neuter (as adverb) publicly, externally -- abroad, + appear, known, manifest, open (+ -ly), outward (+ -ly). see GREEK  (G5316) phaino
From  (G5318) phaneros; to render apparent (literally or figuratively) -- appear, manifestly declare, (make) manifest (forth), shew (self). see GREEK  (G5318) phaneros
Adverb from  (G5318) phaneros; plainly, i.e. Clearly or publicly -- evidently, openly. see GREEK  (G5318) phaneros
From  (G5319) phaneroo; exhibition, i.e. (figuratively) expression, (by extension) a bestowment -- manifestation. see GREEK  (G5319) phaneroo
From  (G5316) phaino; a lightener, i.e. Light; lantern -- lantern. see GREEK  (G5316) phaino
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6439) Pnuw'el); Phanuel (i.e. Penuel), an Israelite -- Phanuel. see HEBREW  (H6439) Pnuw'el

column7: to make visible, to become visible
column9: From a derivative of  (G5316) phaino; to make apparent, i.e. (passively) to appear (neuter participle as noun, a spectacle) -- sight. see GREEK  (G5316) phaino
From a derivative of  (G5324) phantazo; (properly abstract) a (vain) show ("fantasy") -- pomp. see GREEK  (G5324) phantazo
From  (G5324) phantazo; (properly concrete) a (mere) show ("phantasm"), i.e. Spectre -- spirit. see GREEK  (G5324) phantazo
Properly, strengthened from the base of  (G4008) peran or rather of  (G4486) rhegnumi; a gap or chasm, i.e. Ravine (winter-torrent) -- valley. see GREEK  (G4486) rhegnumi see GREEK  (G4008) peran
Of foreign origin ( (H6547) Par'oh); Pharao (i.e. Pharoh), an Egyptian king -- Pharaoh. see HEBREW  (H6547) Par'oh
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6557) Perets); Phares (i.e. Perets), an Israelite -- Phares. see HEBREW  (H6557) Perets

column7: a Pharisee, member of a Jewish religious sect
column9: Of Hebrew origin (compare  (H6567) parash); a separatist, i.e. Exclusively religious; a Pharisean, i.e. Jewish sectary -- Pharisee. see HEBREW  (H6567) parash

column7: the use of medicine, drugs or spells
column9: From  (G5332) pharmakeus; medication ("pharmacy"), i.e. (by extension) magic (literally or figuratively) -- sorcery, witchcraft. see GREEK  (G5332) pharmakeus
From pharmakon (a drug, i.e. Spell-giving potion); a druggist ("pharmacist") or poisoner, i.e. (by extension) a magician -- sorcerer.
